lenges related to suicide, with a reported rate of 22 per 100,000 people in 2000, and research consistently indicates higher suicide rates among females compared to males. This gender disparity underscores the need for targeted mental health interventions for women. \n\nIn recent years, China has seen rapid development in its mental health services, with a shift in focus from severe mental illnesses treated in psychiatric hospitals to broader mental health issues addressed in general hospitals. This evolution reflects an increasing recognition of lifestyle-related diseases and psychosomatic conditions. \n\nInnovative treatments such as repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) are being adopted in some psychiatric institutions to manage conditions like depression, anxiety, and schizophrenia, showcasing advancements in therapeutic approaches. Additionally, China has made significant contributions to mental health research, including the development of the Children's Adaptive Behavior Rating Scale and extensive studies on the prevention and treatment of mental retardation. \n\nOverall, China's mental health landscape is characterized by a blend of traditional practices, modern advancements, and ongoing efforts to address critical issues such as suicide and gender disparities in mental health outcomes."], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-v3"}}}